<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Cadbury proposals adopted by many
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST of the UK's largest companies already comply with the main
recommendations of the Cadbury Committee on the Financial Aspects of
Corporate Governance, a study shows, Norma Cohen writes.
Pensions Investment Research Consultants, which advises pension funds on
corporate governance, found that three-quarters of companies listed in the
FTSE-100 index have separated the offices of chairman and chief executive as
recommended.
The study also found that 75 per cent of companies already have a separate
audit committee of directors with a majority of non-executives. The Cadbury
report recommends that audit committees be composed entirely of
non-executives within two years.
