<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Maastricht deal 'suffers from structural flaws'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BASLE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FLAWS in the Maastricht Treaty increase the difficulties of moves towards
economic and monetary union, Mr Erik Hoffmeyer, chairman of the Committee of
European Community Central Bank Governors, warned yesterday.
Speaking to the Financial Times in Basle, where he is today to report to his
committee on the stalled plans for Emu, Mr Hoffmeyer said the treaty
suffered from 'structural weaknesses' relating to the economic aspects and
from a lack of clarity about the proposed political structure of a united
Europe.
The comments by Mr Hoffmeyer, who is also governor of Denmark's central
bank, increase uncertainty over Emu, plans for which were jeopardised by a
referendum of Danish voters earlier this month rejecting the treaty.
Mr Hoffmeyer, a firm Emu supporter, said he had not been embarrassed by the
vote of his fellow citizens. 'The debate in my country was fair and we have
to respect the decision,' he said, adding that he remained hopeful Europe
could 'get back into the game' of moving towards Emu. But exactly how to
achieve this was a matter for politicians.
The Danish bank chief, who will also take part in today's annual meeting in
Basle of the Bank for International Settlements, the central bankers' bank,
said the tough economic criteria agreed at Maastricht on the terms for
participation in Emu made it unlikely that the whole of Europe could join
the union at the same time.
The treaty also failed to address how wage and fiscal policy across Europe
would have to alter.
Third, the agreement had not been clear enough about the political framework
for a united Europe.
Mr Hoffmeyer said that his country had been wrong to vote against the
Maastricht treaty.
'The decision has retarded the development of a united Europe. I would wish
that my country was about to re-enter (the Emu debate).'
Balanced View: Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
