<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Ireland's anti-Maastricht campaigners out in force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MASS, not Maastricht, was delivered from pulpits across Ireland yesterday.
In churches throughout Dublin, the feast of the Holy Trinity was celebrated,
communion taken and coins placed in collection baskets for the Catholic
Youth Council in response to an appeal from the Archbishop of Dublin. It is
increasingly difficult 'to be young, Irish and Catholic' he said in a
message read in churches throughout the city. Maastricht was not mentioned.
Only at the entrance of the churches, next to noticeboards, the parish
newspapers and the holy water, were copies of the bishops' ambivalent
statement on Maastricht displayed. Most mass-goers appeared to ignore it as
they filed out, as if they had already decided how to vote in Thursday's
referendum.
Less easy to ignore, and far less ambivalent, were the anti-Maastricht
campaigners outside. 'Seven reasons why you should vote No' said the
leaflets they pressed into hands fresh from prayer. Most churches in the
city were similarly staked out.
The No campaign was out in force. One teenager, sporting prominent 'Vote No'
stickers on her blouse, was leafleting on Dublin's beaches at the weekend.
'If you vote Yes, the Maastricht treaty means that abortion will be
introduced in Ireland,' she explained as she handed out 'Pro-Life' leaflets
to half-naked sunbathers. 'What's abortion, mummy?' asked a child with an
ice cream in one hand and a leaflet in the other. 'Give that to me,' said
the embarrassed mother. 'What's Mass-tricked then?' he persisted.
Many Irish people have been asking the same question in the past few weeks.
Confusion is rampant. For some it means Ireland will be wealthier, but women
will have fewer rights because of the special Irish protocol in the treaty,
respecting Ireland's anti-abortion legislation. For others it means Ireland
will be poorer, but women will have more rights because EC law and not Irish
law will prevail.
The government insists Irish neutrality will not be compromised. Articulate
opponents insist that it will. Most people don't know who to believe. A
friend said: 'I'm inclined to vote Yes, but some of the implications are so
unclear I might vote No to be on the safe side'.
A school teacher said he will vote against the treaty because he feared that
the Brussels bureaucracy would become too powerful, and that wealthier
states would benefit more than the poorer ones like Ireland. Another friend,
separated from her husband but unable to divorce because of Ireland's laws
said: 'I am voting Yes because it scares me to be left behind with these
people who want to keep us in the last century.'
Whatever the viewpoint, most are convinced that the opposing camp will win.
The last three opinion polls all indicate a two-to-one margin in favour of
the treaty, although the 'undecided' still account for some 30 per cent of
voters, and most people prefer to believe their own ears rather than the
polls.
The school teacher is convinced the treaty will be approved because the
government and main political parties have all thrown their weight behind
the Yes campaign. 'They have all the resources to get their message across,
while the alternative viewpoint is not getting heard,' he said.
Maybe, but willing bodies to do the canvassing appear to be lacking.
According to Mr Bertie Ahern, the finance minister, the main political
parties were to have launched an all-out effort to put the Yes message
across this weekend. Instead, it was the No campaigners standing at the
church gates, tramping the beaches, knocking on doors and pasting up
posters. The government leaflet, recommending a Yes vote, was delivered last
week in the post.
Boardroom fears Page 10
Garret FitzGerald Page 17
Currencies Page 33
