<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / EC budget talks lead to fears over Irish union vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community foreign ministers will today discuss new EC budget
proposals that could disappoint Irish voters just days before a national
referendum on the Maastricht treaty on European union.
A majority of finance ministers last week came out against a package of
spending increases put forward by Mr Jacques Delors, the Commission
president. His plan for a 30 per cent increase in the EC budget over five
years would benefit poorer countries in the EC, including Ireland, through
larger contributions from richer member states. However, the Portuguese
presidency is now proposing a compromise under which the budget would rise
by the same amount but possibly spread over a longer period, following
opposition from richer member states.
The Irish government will be concerned that any display of rich country
stinginess today might affect the result of its referendum on Maastricht on
Thursday. Recent Irish opinion polls show a slide in pro-EC opinion, though
still with a majority in favour of Maastricht. If Irish voters were to
follow the Danes, who rejected it two weeks ago, the treaty on EC political
and monetary union would be effectively dead.
The Delors plan envisaged a steady rise in spending by a third from next
year to Ecu88bn in 1997. The Portuguese presidency is proposing either
limiting the increase in the first couple of years, or spreading the whole
30 per cent rise beyond 1997.
Dublin's worries are shared by others, including Mr Delors, who told Irish
journalists last week that Ireland could count on continued large cash
benefits from the Community. But Mr Delors has represented his 1993-97
spending plan as 'the bill for Maastricht'. To get the treaty ratified in
richer countries, Delors and the Portuguese presidency, have to accommodate
the desire of richer states to minimise this bill.
Mr Delors has a delicate path to tread, with one false step jeopardising not
only the Maastricht treaty, but also his chances of being re-nominated by EC
leaders at the Lisbon summit in 10 days' time for a further two-year term as
Commission president. At present, he has no rival for the job.
In its paper outlining options for an outline accord at the Lisbon summit on
future EC financing, Portugal suggests that the overall spending rise might
be 'moderated in the initial phase' to suit richer countries which will be
paying in more than they get out of the EC budget. But the poorer countries
 -Spain, Ireland, Greece and Portugal  - would still get 'a linear increase'
in aid from Brussels.
Portugal tentatively hints that the cuts in the Delors plan should come in
spending on EC internal policies, though not in the new scheme for
trans-European transport networks that might especially benefit the
Community's poorer periphery, and on EC external policies.
</TEXT>
