</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Cloudy view from San Francisco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Travelling in the US brings home the vastness of the country. While on the
west coast last week, I went to see Mr Robert Parry, president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco.
Mr Parry is one of a dozen regional Fed presidents, yet runs an empire that
is larger than that of most European central bank governors. It includes
California (which has a larger gross domestic product than all but seven
nations), the western states of Alaska, Arizona, Idaho, Nevada, Oregon and
Washington, and Hawaii and assorted islands in the Pacific. In Europe a
comparable empire might include Britain, Ireland, northern France, Belgium
and the Canary Islands - as a quid pro quo for Hawaii.
How, from this western perch, does Mr Parry see the US economy evolving? His
own district has yet to show definite signs of recovery mainly because of
the drag from California, which is floundering in its worst recession since
the 1930s. Hit especially hard by defence cuts and sagging commercial real
estate markets, the state has lost more than 600,000 jobs (about 4 per cent
of the total). Mr Parry believes California hit bottom at the end of last
year, is now moving sideways and will probably recover later in the year.
Others are more pessimistic, expecting recovery to be postponed to next year
or even 1994.
Nationally, economic statistics are again raising doubts about the
recovery's momentum. I talked with Mr Parry after the release of the May
employment report, which showed unemployment rising sharply to 7.5 per cent
(8.7 per cent in California) but before Thursday's unexpectedly poor retail
sales figures. Optimistic by nature, Mr Parry happily refers to the national
recession in the past tense. 'It lasted two quarters and was over more than
a year ago,' he declares. He believes the economy is poised to break out of
its lengthy slowdown and forecasts growth of close to 3 per cent in the
coming year.
Weak figures for sales, jobs, housing and the money supply, however, are
prompting renewed speculation on Wall Street that the Fed may nudge interest
rates lower again, in spite of its reported shift to a neutral monetary
stance. Can Mr Parry shed any light on the debate?
Choosing his words with care, he says the effects of recent interest rate
cuts are still working their way through the economy. He is 'comfortable'
with the current policy stance because he believes it to be consistent with
moderate economic growth and further progress in reducing inflation.
Reluctant to specify the conditions that would warrant another easing of
policy, he suggests that the Fed's decision last autumn to resume interest
rate cuts set a clear precedent. The implication is that rates could fall
again, but only if a consistent run of weak figures indicates the economy is
sagging into a 'triple dip.'
The silver lining in the long slowdown is a steady decline in inflation.
Friday's consumer prices report confirmed that the underlying rate is now
much closer to 3 per cent than the 5 per cent that seemed entrenched during
the 1980s. Why then are long bond yields still so high?
Mr Parry, an economist by training, blames the Fed's own past failures to
restrain inflation in economic upturns. 'Financial markets don't believe the
Fed will be successful in orchestrating the long-term decline in inflation
I'm predicting. Otherwise the current real rates of interest wouldn't be
needed.' Onerous long-term rates are thus partly an unavoidable price for
past policy mistakes.
Economists at the San Francisco Fed suggest two reasons for macroeconomic
caution in coming months. The first is that the growth slowdown of the past
three years is partly attributable to demographic changes that have caused
the labour force to grow more slowly than in the 1980s. Adjusting for this
supply-side change, the recession has been milder than most previous
downturns. People should not be surprised, therefore, if the recovery is
also weak by past standards.
Perhaps more important, the very diversity of the San Francisco district
makes the bank's economists aware of the limitations of national monetary
policy.
In employment terms, California is experiencing a more severe recession than
that of any region except New England and the mid-Atlantic states. But
California is a huge state: Los Angeles and surrounding counties account for
80 per cent of its job losses; most of northern California is faring no
worse than the nation as a whole. All the other eight states in Mr Parry's
district have enjoyed net job growth since the beginning of the US recession
in July 1990. Star performers such as Utah and Idaho have seen employment
surge by 5 per cent or more.
Mr Parry may sometimes wish he had the power of a European central bank
governor. But if he had his own discount rate, it would still be impossible
to meet the needs of both Los Angeles and the mountain states. Indeed, it
would be wrong to interfere with a rational economic adjustment under way: a
transfer of investment and jobs from overpriced, overpopulated coastal
regions to the cheap, empty interior.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 36
</PAGE>
