<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / US Money and Credit: Hopes rise of cut in interest rates by
Fed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES that the Federal Reserve might ease short-term interest rates once
more in this economic cycle are on the rise again following a batch of
ostensibly helpful statistics.
Yet a strong case can still be made for the Fed keeping its monetary policy
on hold, at least until early July, just before the presidential election
campaign gets under way in earnest.
Those arguing in favour of easing maintain the slow recovery in the economy
remains too fragile for comfort and that a further cut in short-term rates
will help to ensure that the revival is sustainable.
Some support for this line came from last week's statistics. Robust consumer
spending is vital for the recovery yet retail sales showed a tiny two-tenths
of 1 per cent gain in May, while April's figures, originally reported as a
robust 0.9 per cent, were revised down to 0.4 per cent. This was
substantially below analysts' expectations.
However, the weather across the US was atrocious during these two months.
And car sales have been relatively healthy over the past few weeks,
suggesting a cautious willingness to spend on even big ticket items.
The behaviour of M2, the monetary aggregate tracked most closely by the Fed,
which consists of currency, checking accounts and some savings accounts, has
also provided ammunition to the easing school. It was virtually unchanged in
May, and its growth so far this year is far below the Fed's target range.
Yet there is lively debate among economists as to just how relevant M2
should be for Fed decision-making, in view of the markedly different
behaviour of M1, the more narrowly defined aggregate, which has been growing
extremely rapidly.
The main weakness in M2 has been in small-time deposits and money market
mutual fund shares. This may be due in part to depositors shifting savings
into higher earning areas, taking advantage of the large disparity between
the yield on short and long - term instruments.
Mr Elliott Platt, at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, suspects that 'the
strength of M1, coupled with the strength of the savings deposit component
of M2, represents a shift of funds by consumers into forms which can be
readily used for transactions purposes.'
Inflation statistics released on Friday have also given comfort to the
easing school, which argues that they allow the Fed to cut rates without
fear of fuelling inflation. Consumer prices rose a mere one tenth of 1 per
cent in May, the smallest rise since January.
But a key question is the likely effect of a rate cut on the long end of the
credit markets, which influences corporate investment decisions and over
which the Fed has no direct control.
Rates here have remained stubbornly high over the past two years of
short-term easing, producing an extremely steep yield curve. This may be due
in part to international competition for capital and to the US budget
deficit, but residual fears of inflation have also played a substantial
role.
Opinion is divided as to whether another Fed easing would be positive for
the long end, causing yields to fall in line with the short end, or
negative, making yields rise amid fears of higher inflation.
Whatever the case, the Fed seems unlikely to consider moving until it has
substantially more statistical evidence to digest, with the publication of
new unemployment figures on July 2 a possible trigger date. Thereafter, the
presidential campaign will be hotting up, and historically the Fed has been
reluctant to change its stance and give ammunition to the politicians.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
