<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Government Bonds: German bonds take over as star performers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE aftermath of the Danish referendum, Bunds have been the star
performers of the European government security markets - but only in
relative terms.
At the end of last week, the yield on 10-year benchmark government bunds was
in the range of 7.90-7.92 per cent, compared with a yield of around 7.95 per
cent on June 2, the day of the referendum.
This small increase in absolute price terms translates into a considerable
outperformance when compared with soaring yields in other European bond
markets.
The reason? There has been a flight to quality as investors sold
high-yielding bonds which were supposed to benefit from the Maastricht
convergence process. Against the background of uncertainty, bunds offer a
haven.
But the cash realised by selling peseta or lira bonds was not automatically
switched into the bund market: as Mr Reiner Back, senior analyst with
Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt says, there would have been a more definitive
rise in bund prices if this had been so.
'The massive overweight positions in so-called 'convergence plays' - the
story of the last six months - have been unwound,' says Mr Mark
Houghton-Berry at Goldman Sachs in Frankfurt. 'But there has been a general
shift in sentiment away from Europe altogether.'
It appears the cash has gone into high-yielding D-Mark bank accounts - to
the short end of the yield curve - or switched to US or Canadian dollar bond
markets.
The fact is that on strictly fundamental grounds, bunds are no more
attractive than they were a month ago - when investors were worried about
the outlook for German money supply figures, inflation and public spending.
There is no more likelihood now that interest rates will be cut soon - the
fond hope of overseas investors who bought heavily after rates were lifted
to historically high levels last December.
Economists remain convinced a cut is unlikely to happen until the latter
part of the year at the earliest, and perhaps not this year at all.
Mr Back predicts a wave of buying later this month and next as the headline
inflation figures show a definite drop. He forecasts year-on-year inflation
will be 4.2 per cent this month and 3.3 per cent for July, against 4.6 per
cent in April.
Mr Robert Barrie, European economist with BZW Securities in London, says the
sharp drop in the inflation rate expected for next month is largely due to
last summer's mineral oil tax rises dropping out of the calculation.
The outlook for underlying inflation is still poor, and this, not the
headline rate, is likely to influence the Bundesbank's interest rate policy.
</TEXT>
