<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / UK Gilts: Prices slide on convergence worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORRIES about the long-term pattern of economic convergence across Europe
conspired with concern about the volume of gilt supply to push down prices,
especially at the long end of the yield curve.
These potential sources of turbulence for the market overshadowed a run of
good news on inflation, which indicated that pressures pushing up prices of
UK goods and services over the next year will be extremely small.
Investors are concerned that the progress made in the past year in bringing
gilt yields closer to those for German and French government bonds may soon
grind to a halt, as a result of doubts about whether European economic and
monetary union will take place as planned.
At the same time, the large volume of funding to finance Britain's growing
public sector deficits will probably drive yields upwards, particularly for
long-dated gilts.
Reflecting these fears, the long dated 9 per cent Treasury stock 2008 saw a
yield rise of 6 basis points, from 8.95 per cent to 9.01 per cent. The price
fell by just over half a point, to 99 13/16 .
At the short end, interest was greater, and yields for short-dated gilts
rose only marginally, if at all. For example, the 10 per cent Treasury stock
maturing in 1994 saw its yield unchanged at 9.24 per cent. Its price was
quoted on Friday night at 101 11/32 .
These trends reflect a tendency over the past month for investors to switch
down the yield curve, avoiding longer dated securities due to the funding
worries.
There is particular concern about whether the Bank of England will be able
to sell the Pounds 2bn or so of long-dated stock it is expected to auction
on June 24, without forcing up yields.
Meanwhile, the pace of the funding programme - to finance a public spending
deficit expected to be more than Pounds 30bn in 1992-1993 - was underlined
by the Bank's announcement on Friday that it is to issue Pounds 500m of 4
1/8 per cent index linked Treasury stock due in 2030 from today. The stock
is at the far end of the yield curve, of a maturity range unfamiliar to many
gilt specialists.
The market was, however, cheered by the rash of data on inflation which
indicated an extremely slow recovery from the UK recession, an event which
will put little rising pressure on gilt yields and should put a floor under
prices:
The rate of retail price inflation in the UK was unchanged last month, but
underlying trends remained on a downward path. A 0.4 per cent rise in the
retail prices index in May left the rate of increase in the 12 months to May
at 4.3 per cent, the same as in April. The RPI excluding mortgage interest
payments fell to 5.3 per cent in the year to May, the lowest since December
1988.
A Confederation of British Industry distributive trades survey said shop
prices were rising more slowly than at any time since the survey started in
1983. It also said any recovery in retail sales was likely to be sluggish
after the depressed state of this sector over the past 18 months.
The prices of manufactured goods leaving Britain's factories rose by 3.6 per
cent in May, the lowest annual rate of increase for five years. The producer
prices index, often taken as a measure of core inflation, rose 0.1 per cent
on the month, compared with a 0.4 per cent monthly rise in April, supporting
government hopes that upward pressure on prices will continue to ease.
Further evidence of the disinflationary momentum in the UK economy came from
the rise in the index excluding volatile food, drink and tobacco prices.
This rose by 0.2 per cent in May compared with the previous month, bringing
the year-on-year rate of change to 2.7 per cent, the lowest since June 1967.
</TEXT>
