<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / International Company News: Credit quality warning on
Japanese banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO and MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CREDIT quality of Japan's leading banks will remain under pressure
through most of this decade, warns Moody's Investment Service, the US credit
rating agency.
In The Future of the Japanese Banking System, a report to be published this
week, Moody's concludes Japanese banks will lose their stature as
international banks as they concentrate on low-risk domestic businesses.
Moody's expects the average rating for Japanese banks - currently between
Aa3 and A1 - to continue to decline, but remain in the A range through the
mid-1990s.
Japanese banks face a severe squeeze on profits due to loans stemming from
property related lending. Between 1984 and 1990, loans to property companies
rose from 6.6 per cent to 10.3 per cent of Japanese banks' domestic loans.
The banks, burdened by large unrealised losses, have also been hard hit by
the sharp fall in Japan's stock markets.
The gross amount of problem loans, including restructured loans, is well
over 10 per cent of portfolios at the weaker institutions. 'Japanese banking
has never faced asset quality deterioration of the scale in the postwar
period,' says Moody's.
Despite these problems, Japanese banks will not fail or default on deposits
or bonds, thanks to Japanese regulatory protection. However, Moody's points
out the financial authorities are using this crisis as an opportunity to
restructure the banking system.
Rather than recapitalise banks or materially improve their profitability,
the authorities are looking to change the shape of the system through
mergers and ultimately to reduce the size and role of the financial system
itself.
Due to the pressure on earnings and capital ratios, banks' strategy will
shift from market share to profitability, focusing on the quality of
borrowers rather than loan volumes.
In the international markets, credit concerns have increased international
funding costs for Japanese banks.
But Moody's points out the effect on Japan's economy will be limited, since
corporate funding needs will be met by borrowing in the growing debt
securities markets.
Moody's has upgraded its rating of the debt of Chemical Bank, citing the
progress it has made to cut costs, increase revenues and improve
capitalisation following last year's merger with New York rival
Manufacturers Hanover, writes Martin Dickson in New York.
The rating of the senior long term debt was raised to Baa1 from Baa2.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
