<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / International Company News: IRI sets price for share
'packets' in STET sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRI, Italy's biggest state holding company, has set a price of L2,020,000
(Dollars 1,692) for each of the 'packets' of shares and warrants in the
latest dilution of its stake in the STET telecommunications group.
Investors have been keenly awaiting the price for the placement, which,
including warrants, will match last year's rights issue by Generali as the
biggest capital raising made by an Italian company.
STET is the IRI-owned holding company which controls Italy's state-owned
telecommunications activities, notably SIP, the main operating utility. Net
profits last year were L1,413bn on sales of L22,946bn.
Investors will be offered packets containing 1,000 ordinary STET shares, 50
warrants convertible into a further 500 ordinary shares, and 100 warrants
convertible into 1,000 savings shares.
IRI said the first group of warrants will be convertible into ordinary
shares at L2,100 a share, while the price for the savings shares linked to
the second tranche of warrants will be L2,000 a share.
Based on the closing price for STET's ordinary shares in Milan on Friday,
the packets represent a discount of around 5.7 per cent, against their
hypothetical market value of L2,143,000 each.
After all the warrants are exercised IRI's stake in STET will fall to 53 per
cent of the ordinary shares and just 1 per cent of the savings stock. IRI
currently owns around 69 per cent of the ordinary stock and 30 per cent of
the savings shares, if all outstanding warrants are exercised.
The European Commission remains concerned by new Italian legislation
governing stock market reform. Sir Leon Brittan, the EC's competition
commissioner, said in Milan: 'We are very concerned about this and have
indicated that' to the Italian authorities.
The Commission's objections focus on the law introducing Societa di
Intermediazione Mobiliare (SIM), Italy's new stockbroking and fund
management hybrid. Several countries have objected that the SIMs law
discriminates against financial institutions from outside Italy.
'We have had complaints from more than one country,' said Sir Leon. The
objections 'seem to have considerable substance. It is difficult to
reconcile this legislation with the rules of the European Community as they
stand.'
