<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / International Company News: FT-SE 100 Index and Irish
companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FT-SE 100 Index Steering Committee has issued the following statement:
An Irish company has complained to the EC Commission about the rules that
exclude non-UK companies from the FT-SE 100 index, arguing that these
discriminate against Irish companies.
Though the complaint names the London Stock Exchange, the ground rules for
the FT-SE index are set and interpreted by a committee of independent
representatives of users of the market, and not by the London Stock
Exchange.
Mr Peter Jones, chairman of the steering committee, replying to the Irish
company and to newspaper articles discussing its request for inclusion in
the index, has previously stated:
'The FT-SE 100 was specifically, and very deliberately, designed to be an
indicator of the performance of the UK market.
'The change of rules needed to allow non-UK companies to enter the index -
whether Irish, American or Japanese - would be a fundamental change to the
design of the index.'
The London Stock Exchange has replied to the commission's preliminary
inquiry, making it clear that in its view the complaint is misconceived in
fact and law.
The steering committee endorses the London Stock Exchange's response.
</TEXT>
