<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / International Company News: 3i puts off flotation until next
year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
3i, the UK venture capital group, has been forced into yet another delay of
its planned flotation by the slowness of the economic recovery. It had
originally hoped to list its shares early this year, then shifted its sights
to November but has now postponed the date until next year.
As part of preparations for a float 3i plans further cost-saving measures on
top of those which have already reduced annual outgoings by Pounds 12m.
The company is only half way through a cost-cutting programme which has seen
staff numbers cut by a third to 670 over the past 18 months, and a reduction
from 11 to six in the number of senior managers, according to Mr Ewen
Macpherson, managing director.
Future savings will be achieved by a slow-down in recruitment and a
streamlining of administration systems rather than by redundancies. 3i plans
to make more extensive use of credit scoring techniques to assess new and
existing investments in preference to more subjective assessment techniques.
The short-term pressures normally associated with a stock market listing
will not lead to any changes in long-term investment policy, Mr Macpherson
said.
A study of 3i's investments by Prof Dick Brealey, of London Business School,
showed that its portfolio of unquoted investments had a natural dynamism
greater than that of investment trusts invested in quoted stocks.
Unquoted companies had a one in 10 chance of being taken over in a year
compared with quoted companies which had a one in 50 chance, the research
showed. This meant that very few companies stayed in 3i's portfolio for more
than 10 years.
These findings are of crucial importance to 3i. It has made great play of
being a long-term investor which does not pressurise the managements it
backs to sell off or float their companies.
But there are aspects of the way 3i does business which will change as a
result of the planned flotation. It believes its accounting policies have
been excessively conservative and will be more generous in future in valuing
its unquoted holdings.
It is also considering the possibility of increasing its involvement in the
management of other company's venture capital portfolios. It already manages
investments for three small investment trusts and expects further
opportunities to occur as a result of the consolidation presently under way
in the venture capital industry.
</TEXT>
