<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Banks shore up shaky property foundations / Explaining the
fashion for behind-the-scenes rescues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospects for the UK commercial property industry, locked into its third
year of decline, are as diverse and uncertain as ever.
For every investor who asserts that the slump is over - as Mr John Ritblat,
chairman of British Land, did last Thursday - there is a developer who
claims that the bottom is not even in sight. Thus, Regalian's accounts were
qualified last week on the grounds that its development sites and empty
property defied precise valuation.
But the biggest sources of uncertainty are the banks. Tremors from last
month's spectacular corporate failures are rippling through the UK property
market, prompting speculation about the next large property company to
collapse.
Although Mountleigh's failure was long-expected, the collapse of Canary
Wharf has disconcerted an industry that thought it was hardened to bad news.
More than a third of investment and development companies recently
interviewed by Gallup expected the clearing banks to clamp down on their
credit lines as a result of the Canary Wharf collapse. The prospect of more
corporate failures is perceived to be not a question of if, but when.
But fears of a sudden melt-down are probably misplaced. The character of
this property slump is very different from that of 1974, when defaults by
property companies threatened to trigger the failure of the secondary banks.
This time round, most of the lending is syndicated amongst large banks which
are better able to absorb the losses.
As a result, one of the most striking features of this property slump is the
support shown by the banks for companies which appear to be prime candidates
for receivership.
A cursory glance at the share prices listed at the back of this newspaper
shows that a large number of quoted trading and development companies are
nearly worthless. The difficulty of letting and selling buildings has forced
scores of companies to breach banking covenants and left them without
sufficient income to service bank debt.
But for the most part, banks are responding to companies' pleas to defer
their interest payments or reconstruct their debts. For every high-profile
failure, there are many more successful rescues behind the scenes.
The banks' patience can be ascribed to a combination of common sense,
desperation and wishful thinking.
The most convincing reason for the banks' forbearance is that they would
gain nothing from putting a company into receivership. They would prefer to
leave the company in the hands of the management than pay handsomely for
receivers who have limited property expertise.
'Banks would far rather work with, not against, the incumbent management who
know the assets best,' said Sir John Quinton, chairman of Barclays Bank, the
biggest UK lender to the property industry.
Exceptions occur where the banks have lost faith in the company's
management. The failure of Mountleigh, for instance, was partly due to the
City's exasperation with its frequent changes of management and strategy. It
was also due to the presence of bondholders demanding payment, another
common cause of receiverships. Banks are often reluctant to allow
bondholders, who have a lesser claim to the company's assets, to take money
out of the business.
Another crucial incentive for the banks to avoid receiverships is the impact
it has on asset values. A survey published by English &amp; Overseas Properties
last week found that four out of five of the UK's top 30 receivers believed
that banks were reluctant to put assets under receivership for fear of
realising massive losses in asset values.
The problem is partly that potential buyers force down prices when companies
are in receivership. Although the receivers invariably stress that they 'are
not looking for distress sales', a company in receivership undoubtedly has
less bargaining power. 'Receivership has an unfortunate taint' said one of
Canary Wharf's bankers, explaining its choice of administration rather than
receivership.
A related problem is that assets deteriorate under receivership. Creditors
often believe it is throwing good money after bad to fund property
maintenance. The budget set aside by the banks is exclusively for marketing
purposes, rather than for enhancing or improving the building to retain its
value.
But in some instances, the most important motivation for keeping a company
going is that the banks want to minimise their provisions.
Selling property crystallises a loss and in the current state of the market,
the resultant damage to a bank's balance sheet would tend to be greater than
if it estimated the fall in value. Banks would rather take provisions over a
two- or three-year period. They will want to avoid provisions and write-offs
that shrink their capital at a time when the Bank for International
Settlements' new capital adequacy regime is being introduced.
Critics argue that banks' willingness to keep property companies in business
largely stems from a desire to take the simplest approach rather than add to
the daunting problems already on their plate.
A perception exists that the banks are floundering where their property
loans are concerned. A head of a large surveying firm, recently drafted in
by one of the clearing banks to help with the property casualties,
discovered huge numbers of doubtful property loans stuffed into files in
alphabetical order. 'They just don't know what they've got,' he says.
Banks are also criticised in some quarters for believing that holding back
on receiverships will help foster a recovery, which will ultimately allow
them to get more back from delinquent loans.
As matters stand, the market is deadlocked. At the top end of the market,
representing 15 per cent of the total, there is unsatisfied demand, which
could be slaked by property coming on the market. 'More receiverships will
bring liquidity to the market. It will bring investors in at more realistic
levels which will enhance the market,' says Mr Mike Riley of Chesterton,
chartered surveyors.
For the remainder of the market, the problem is an absence of finance, as
banks are not prepared to extend new loans on property that is in any way
flawed. 'Unless the banking sector starts lending and takes more risk, it
will be very difficult to finance a recovery,' says Mr Riley.
This poses a large question over the banks' ability to extricate themselves
from their problem property loans.
Memories of the last property crash when the banks were able, with time, to
work through their problems are misleading. Inflation reduced the scale of
those debts; yet now indebted companies are suffering from one of the
highest level of interest rates, adjusted for inflation, since the 1930s.
Problems created by the banks' headlong rush into property lending at the
end of the 1980s are likely to be around for some years yet.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-2855</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5ABYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Financial reporting of banks criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY LARGE banks around the world use hidden reserves to conceal their true
results and provide poor examples of financial reporting, according to an
analysis conducted by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick and Lafferty Business
Research.
Australian and Canadian banks provide the best quality information in their
annual accounts while their German and Austrian competitors the worst, the
study concludes.
Only eight of the leading 100 banks worldwide are considered to have
financial reporting of notably high quality in their accounts, while 20
score less than 40 per cent in ratings devised by Peats, auditor to more
than one third of the banks described.
Australia and New Zealand Banking Group, the Bank of Montreal and the Royal
Bank of Canada are among the highest rated. The lowest score was given to
Zentralsparkasse und Kommerzialbank in Austria, now part of Bank Austria.
The ratings awarded three-quarters of total points for the provision of
financial information such as statements on accounting policies and
information on non-performing loans, and one quarter for other information
like employment practices and strategy statements.
Many banks outside the Anglo-Saxon world make use of hidden reserves or
excess general provisions which are not disclosed and cannot be quantified
by users of accounts.
Most banks do not reveal sufficient information on their provisions for bad
debts, and only 14 reported the interest written-off on non-performing
loans.
'The Swiss have improved their reporting in the last few years, but Germany
is still pretty abysmal,' said Mr Michael Lafferty, one of the authors.
British banks ranked about average in the survey, with Bank of Scotland and
Barclays performing best. But few provided much information on their
directors or employment practices.
Eleven received a qualified report from auditors, expressing doubts about
information in the accounts. The Bank of Taiwan does not contain an
auditor's report at all.
Bank annual reports. 1992 world survey. Lafferty Publications, 4th floor,
Diana House, 33-34 Chiswell Street, London EC1Y 4SE. Pounds 545
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
