<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / The Lex Column: Electricity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's annual results from East Midlands Electricity should show pre-tax
profits up by more than a third. As other regional electricity companies
report, that might come to look positively modest. Norweb is set to report
more than doubled pre-tax profits, while its earnings per share will be
perhaps 130 per cent higher.
To be fair, there is an element of catch-up, thanks to the government's
underestimate of inflation in the year of privatisation. But that will
scarcely cut much ice with customers and politicians. Nor, given the
pressure on other utilities, will it be sufficient to protect the RECs from
greater scrutiny by their own regulator. It is hard to see how Offer can
avoid commenting on the scale of the profits growth, even if only to stress
that customers must benefit as well as shareholders.
On that front, the companies face a dilemma. Privately, many of the RECs
admit that they can sustain 8 per cent real dividend increases for the
foreseeable future. Yet that is twice as much as the government allowed for
at privatisation. To date, Professor Littlechild has stuck firmly to a
long-term view of his industry. Doubtless he will gradually take a less
academic approach. Until it becomes clear what that means for dividends,
prudent investors will doubtless prefer the slightly safer water sector.
</TEXT>
