<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / The Lex Column: Steel
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Steel's results - and probable dividend cut - are two weeks away. It
is worth considering the market backdrop against which the payout will be
determined. The price increases of some 3 to 4 per cent imposed by European
steel producers in the first quarter stuck at the time. But thanks partly to
the industry's failure to manage a cut in supply, the market has turned soft
again. There are scant grounds for expecting an upturn in demand, given the
weak outlook for the European economy dictated by Germany's tight monetary
policy, surplus capacity in eastern Europe and the anaemic US recovery.
The immediate prospects thus hardly give British Steel an incentive to err
on the side of generosity. Investors are probably right to expect at best a
final dividend of 1.5p against 5.75p last year. Admittedly, there are
belated signs of European production being reined back. That could show
through in pricing from the mid-year onwards. Perhaps the market could be
kick-started if the prospect of higher prices persuaded customers to rebuild
their stocks. But that seems fanciful if, as County NatWest calculates, 11
per cent of Europe's hot-rolled steel capacity is surplus to requirements.
All the same, British Steel could yet prove one of the great European
survivors in its industry. Its rationalisation programme has given it an
edge in terms of cost. But its problem remains the snail's pace at which
cutbacks are proceeding elsewhere in Europe. Even high-cost German producers
are reluctant to get out, as the acrimony over the Krupp takeover of Hoesch
shows. The biggest danger is that as European interest rates fall, economic
recovery next year may create an excuse for further delay in
rationalisation. That could make British Steel's efficiency less relevant in
the context of a market beset with chronic subsidised oversupply.
</TEXT>
