<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / The Lex Column: Markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week's dividend cut from Pilkington and dividend warning from Taylor
Woodrow were a reminder of the fragility of UK equity values. On a rolling
12-month basis, growth in UK dividends may now be a mere 1 per cent. In
calendar 1992 it could be little better, in which case dividends will have
lagged inflation for the third year running. In past recessions, the fall in
real dividends was more severe. But these were times of high inflation and
lower or negative real interest rates, making the alternatives of cash or
bonds more unattractive still.
Today, the choice between asset classes is made harder by fresh uncertainty
about inflation. If the Maastricht treaty falls apart, the UK's commitment
to the ERM may come under renewed scrutiny. It used to be argued that if ERM
membership meant the UK could enjoy German inflation rates, gilts no longer
needed to offer the same yield premium over equities. If that principle is
being challenged at the same time as real dividends continue to fall, what
price the yield ratio?
The conservative answer would be to trust to equities, however bad the
short-term outlook for dividends. The belief that inflation is conquered is
less convincing at the bottom of the economic cycle than it would be at the
top. And while the importance of a fixed exchange rate system in controlling
inflation is real enough, it is worth recalling that when gilt yields first
rose above equity yields, in the 1950s and 1960s, sterling was a member of
the ERM's predecessor, Bretton Woods.
</TEXT>
