<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / The Lex Column: GPA on the runway
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The latest airline price war in the US is unfortunately timed from GPA's
point of view. It may be a short-term phenomenon, but it is a sober reminder
that the fortunes of the world's biggest aircraft leasing group ultimately
depend on the profitability of its customers. As BA's annual report pointed
out last week, airlines' losses on international scheduled services totalled
Dollars 4bn last year. Investors will be unwise therefore to subscribe for
GPA's public offer if they are not confident that the air transport sector
is set to resume its upward flight path in the mid and late 1990s.
It is hard to fault GPA's recent record. The company has come through a
turbulent period with minimal damage to earnings. It has an enviable, and
possibly unparalleled, knowledge of the market, notably of the smaller
carriers and the associated credit risks. It is financially innovative, as
last week's successful Dollars 520m issue of securitised aircraft leases
clearly demonstrated.
This capacity to raise new capital, though, is crucial to GPA's long-term
survival, as the prospectus frankly admits. There are commitments to buy
almost Dollars 12bn of new aircraft by the end of the century, but only
enough money in the kitty to take the group through to next June. So far GPA
has avoided the worst effects of declining lease rates and lower residual
values - but it cannot do so indefinitely without a market recovery. It has
been hard for the advisers to price the risks - but a prospective 9-10 times
multiple is probably fair at this uncertain stage in the cycle.
</TEXT>
