<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Letter: Accountability the essential feature of corporate
well-being
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr MAURICE GILLIBRAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, However much I disagree with Sir Owen Green's approach to corporate
governance (Personal View, June 9) his contribution must be welcomed as a
stimulant to the debate on this vital issue.
Accountability is an essential feature of any corporate activity if it is to
be effective and efficient. The inability of British businesses to compete
with their counterparts in Germany and Japan since the Second World War is a
consequence of the erosion of the accountability of the managers of the
businesses to the shareholders. Accountability, according to the Companies
Act, is vested in the authority of the annual general meeting of
shareholders. Regrettably, this has been rendered ineffective by the
automatic support of existing managements by the proxy votes of the
institutions. Accordingly, managements have become self-perpetuating and
fail to realise the full potential of the business.
However, Sir Owen opposes even the limited strengthening of accountability
as proposed by the Cadbury Committee. He regards the appointment of
non-executive directors with responsibilities to monitor the interests of
shareholders as being against the principles of a unitary board. He goes
even further and challenges those who believe in a need to monitor the
activities of the executive to have the courage of their convictions and
advocate a two-tier board structure. On this point I find myself in full
agreement with Sir Owen.
Maurice Gillibrand,
7 Tal-y-Cae,
Tregarth,
Bangor, Gwynedd
</TEXT>
