<DOCNO>FT922-2868</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5ABLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Leading Article: Many roads from Rio
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE RIO conference was worth having
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
once. It should not be repeated. A conclave of nearly 150 heads of
government addressing all the world's problems simultaneously is not a forum
from which immediately useful results can reasonably be expected. Yet the
Earth Summit was not a complete waste of time. Its value is in the first
instance educational; beyond that the treaties that have been signed may in
due course begin to influence the future actions of governments. They should
certainly give a fillip to the most powerful agency for environmental
protection: public opinion.
No one can now ignore the pressure to reduce emissions that contribute to
global warming. Those who, like the US government, are sceptical about
scientific forecasts of a greenhouse effect appear to have been brought
round to an appreciation of the logic behind the precautionary principle.
This suggests that some measures to curb CO and other destructive gases are
worth taking today because the damage that will be done if the scientists
are even half-right is so great. The price of insurance is relatively low.
Again, the protection of endangered species is a universally accepted goal,
embraced by President George Bush as well as by the 139 countries that did
sign the relevant treaty. The driving force is economic as well as
ecological. Proper management of forests is an acknowledged ambition; even
the Malaysians are aware of the potential force of customer resistance to
the purchase of tropical hardwoods. There may be no treaty but if there are
reluctant customers the growers will want to proclaim their sustainable
management of forests. If not much was said in Rio about the most
destructive phenomenon of them all - overpopulation - the very omission of
the topic should have served to remind many of the participants of its
importance.
Soft treaties
So much for the good news. The hard truth is that the agreements concluded
at the conference necessarily reflect the lowest common denominator of
national interests. The treaties are soft. The binding declarations are
loose. The agreements to disagree are dead-ends. This outcome is in itself
part of the educational process. The group of 77 developing countries cannot
be blamed for trying to see how much the rich world is willing to pay for
environmental protection; its leaders go home with a clearer understanding
that the amount is small, while the terms upon which it will be released are
strict.
Summit lessons
That is perhaps the principal lesson of the summit. It was conducted as if
it was an away-meeting of the United Nations General Assembly. As such it
once again demonstrated that the demands of the many would always be
rejected by the few. The framers of the UN charter were well aware of this
defect of mass meetings. That is why they put in place a Security Council
whose permanent members reflected the global balance of power. If the UN is
to adopt protection of the environment as a goal equal in importance to
keeping the peace it must establish a similar top-level steering committee.
This might evolve out of the proposed Sustainable Development Commission.
Its membership should reflect the balance of economic power while not
allowing the interests of business to override those of either
environmentalists or the developing world.
A second lesson is that no human organisation can tackle everything in one
meeting. It is true in theory that protection of the environment is bound up
with both development and population control, but specific issues in each
area need specific solutions. The Montreal convention on phasing out CFCs,
the gases that damage the ozone layer, is a good example. Public pressure
has built on this, and CFCs are on their way out. Greenhouse gases need at
least one treaty, one convention and one monitoring mechanism to themselves;
perhaps CO needs its own international agreement. Forests need another.
Endangered species a third. The Rio meeting, with its several mechanisms for
further action, has made a hazy start, but if there is to be genuine
progress before the end of the century the proper disaggregation of
environmental strategies is a necessary first step.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-2869</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5ABKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You can hardly watch television while pottering about the garden on long
June evenings, but you can listen to the radio, and as usual there are
tempting offers.
Radio 3 transmits the first of four concerts called Bach, The Colourful
Dramatist (7.30), which includes umpteen cantatas and the Fourth
Brandenburg.
The Monday Play is Short The Season (8.00 Radio 4), a first play for radio
by Mike McGrath, son of an Irish kennel man, who has set his action in Irish
kennels where the kennel huntsman comes into conflict with the anti-hunt
daughter of the groom.
A new Book At Bedtime begins at 10.45 (Radio 4): 'A British Picture',
autobiography of Ken Russell, eccentric film maker, who will be the nightly
reader.
The last in the present season of Horizon (8.00 BBC2) sets out to undermine
the idea of the white-coated scientist. A group of molecular biology
researchers at Manchester University used a home video camera to record
their everyday lives.
In the fifth of the Female Parts series (9.00 C4) 13-year- old London girls
discuss Aids and teenage pregnancy.
</TEXT>
