<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / People: Mercury tries harder at unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury Asset Management, one of the biggest and most aggressive London fund
managers, has poached Richard Royds, the 34-year-old managing director of
John Govett Unit Trusts, to head its own unit trust operation, one of the
weaker parts of MAM's business.
Royds, who will take over as managing director of Mercury Fund Managers in
early July, helps fill a gap at the top which has existed since James
Dawnay, 45, left to join Martin Currie Investment Management last November.
Dawnay was replaced as chairman of Mercury Fund Managers by David Rosier,
41, who will continue to hold this post in addition to his other
responsibilities. Nicholas Stewart, 37, the current managing director,
becomes vice chairman.
Royds' appointment is the clearest sign to date of MAM's intention of
beefing up its unit trust business, which has been overshadowed by its far
more successful pension fund management operation. Although MAM's unit
trusts have around Pounds 1.7bn of funds, and rank tenth in size in the
industry, this represents only a small part of a group which manages around
Pounds 40bn in total.
Whilst MAM's decision to look outside the group to strengthen its unit trust
team is no surprise, the choice of Royds may be. After a stint at Capital
Radio and the Media Shop, he is a relatively late entrant to the unit trust
game, only joining Wardley Unit Trust Managers in 1986 and John Govett in
1988.
While his rise has been rapid, the firm he comes from is hardly yet one of
the unit trust industry's great success stories. At the end of last year
Govett ranked 72nd in terms of the size of funds under management - although
chief executive Kevin Pakenham points out how ' a very successful year to
date' has achieved net sales of Pounds 40m plus, with notable successes in
selling innovative futures fund products.
'One of the great problems of the unit trust business is that it has tended
to recycle funds within the industry' according to Rosier. To attempt to
break that pattern, Mercury needs a much more diversified product range.
Meanwhile Pakenham says that Royds' departure ' leaves a 'personality', but
not necessarily a large 'business', gap.
*****
Richard Young is the new finance director of SUNLEIGH, the USM company which
has recently moved out of engineering and into leisure products. With the
switch - to PowaKaddy electronic golf trollies, Laser dinghies and Dart
catamarans - came a move of the company's headquarters from Yorkshire to
Maidenhead. The previous finance director was not prepared to come south,
opening up the opportunity for 46-year-old Taylor.
He has switched from the position of finance director at the UK subsidiary
of Crane Corporation, where the product range included pipe fittings, valves
and pumps. A chartered accountant, he spent 12 years with ITT in Brussels
and the rest of Continental Europe, before returning to the UK for a spell
with Sun Microsystems.
</TEXT>
