<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Economics: Looking for 'green shoot' indicators of UK
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HOST of indicators on the the UK economy will be released this week.
Evidence of economic recovery is still thin so the figures - in particular
data on industrial production, retail sales, and unemployment - will be
scrutinised for signs of 'green shoots'.
After May's sunny beginning there were high expectations for the month's
retail sales, but reports from individual retailers suggest that the
half-hearted post-election spending spree dwindled last month.
There are higher hopes for manufacturing output, which has risen for two
consecutive months. On a three-monthly trend basis the decline in output
appears to be over and the forecast is for another modest rise.
The following are some of the other economic highlights and events of the
week. The figures in brackets are the median of City economists' forecasts,
from MMS International: Today: UK, first quarter balance of payments (Pounds
2.1bn deficit); France, May consumer prices index (up 0.3 per cent on month,
up 3.2 per cent on year); US, auto sales June 1-10; Canada, April wage
settlement increases (up 2.6 per cent); Australia, April housing finance (up
5 per cent); Switzerland, Bank of International Settlements AGM in Basel;
Luxembourg, EC General Affairs Council meets to discuss 1993-97 budget.
Tomorrow: UK, May PSBR (Pounds 4bn); US, May housing starts (1.17m), May
building permits, May industrial production (up 0.5 per cent); May capacity
utilisation (79 per cent), first quarter current account; Canada, March
leading indicator (flat), April manufacturing unfilled orders (flat); Japan,
industrial production.
Wednesday: UK, May retail sales (up 0.2 per cent on month, up 1.5 per cent
on year), April industrial production (up 0.6 per cent), April manufacturing
output (up 0.2 per cent on month, down 0.5 per cent on year); US, first
quarter productivity; Canada, first quarter manufacturing capacity
utilisation (71 per cent); US, Fed releases Tan Book for June 30 FOMC.
Thursday: UK, May unemployment (up 30,000), April average earnings (7.25 per
cent), April unit wage costs (4.2 per cent), May M0 (down 0.2 per cent on
month, up 2.1 per cent on year), May M4 (up 0.4 per cent on month, up 5.4
per cent on year), May M4 lending (up Pounds 2.5bn); US, initial claims for
week ended June 6 (400,000), April merchandise trade balance (Dollars 5.5bn
deficit), exports (Dollars 37.3bn), imports (Dollars 42.7bn), money supply
data for week ended June 8; Canada, April merchandise exports (up 0.55 per
cent), imports (up 0.2 per cent), trade surplus (Dollars 1bn); Ireland,
referendum on ratification of Maastricht treaty; Europe, markets closed:
Dusseldorf, Munich, Stuttgart and Frankfurt and in Austria and Portugal.
Friday: UK, CBI monthly industrial trends; France, April industrial
production (up 0.5 per cent); US, May Treasury budget (Dollars 50bn
deficit); Canada, May CPI (up 0.4 per cent); Sweden, markets closed.
During the week: Germany, May producer prices index (up 0.3 per cent on
month, up 2.1 per cent on year), May M3 from fourth quarter base (up 8.5 per
cent); Italy, April wholesale prices index (up 1.8 per cent on year), April
producer prices index (up 1.6 per cent on year), April industrial production
(up 3 per cent on year); Netherlands, April trade balance; Denmark, May CPI
(up 0.5 per cent on month, up 2.3 per cent on year); Japan, GDP.
</TEXT>
