<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Support for flexible pension age
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FLEXIBLE rather than a common fixed pension age for men and women is
favoured by 60 per cent of managers, according to a British Institute of
Management survey published today.
The finding will add to pressure on the government to move from its position
of favouring a fixed age. Under a fixed plan, the age women would become
eligible for a state pension would rise from 60 to either 63 or 65 - the
current pension age for men.
Of those managers surveyed who wanted a flexible approach to retirement,
three-quarters favoured a scheme which would enable people to claim a larger
state pension the later they retired.
One in six wanted a split scheme under which part of the state pension would
be payable at 60 and the rest at 65.
Of 3,000 BIM members surveyed, 330 responded.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
