<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Venture capitalists launch value study
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE venture-capital industry is to carry out a pilot study aimed at
gathering the first reliable statistics on the performance of its
investments.
The move is in response to pressure from institutional investors
disappointed with the industry's poorer-than-expected performance and
concerned to see they get value for money.
The British Venture Capital Association will gather performance data on
investments by six of its members. A project team will gather information on
the performance of individual investments to see whether a common pattern
emerges from investments made in a particular year or in a particular type
of deal. It may also look at the returns from investments in particular
industries.
But the data will not be used to compare the performance of different funds,
a prospect which worries many venture capitalists. Nor will it reveal the
return to investors from particular investments, because different funds
levy different fees and charges before passing on profits to investors.
Mr Robert Drummond, chairman of the association and managing director of
Grosvenor Venture Managers, said: 'My hope is that the data will allow us to
explain to the world where we are successful and get away from a
concentration on the deals which have run into problems such as the buy-outs
of MFI, Magnet or Isosceles' The pilot project is also intended to establish
a standardised method of assessing the return on venture-capital
investments. It comes two years after the association agreed common
guidelines on valuing investments, although these rules still leave room for
variation.
The venture-capital association is to begin a review of its valuation
guidelines with the aim of simplifying them.
The results of the study are expected to be available early next year.
</TEXT>
