<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Managing agents' rules eased by Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S of London, the troubled insurance market, has lifted the requirement
that managing agents must obtain insurance against negligence claims.
But managing agents who do not have cover are unlikely to be able to attract
new business, and the move is seen as hastening the shake-out of weaker
managing agents.
Lloyd's Names - whose private wealth stands behind insurance claims - are
unlikely to wish to place business with underwriters who in effect cannot be
sued for negligence.
Claims against so-called 'errors and omissions' policies have soared in the
past 18 months and premiums for that type of insurance have become a
significant part of managing agents' costs. Managing agents manage
underwriting syndicates.
Mr Dick Hazell, Lloyd's deputy chairman, said last week in a letter to Names
that 'severe difficulties have been experienced in establishing a viable
market for such insurance this year and it seems likely that the situation
may be even more uncertain next year'.
Mr Hazell acknowledged that removal of the mandatory requirement for errors
and omissions insurance could cause 'understandable concern'. However, he
said that Lloyd's Council would continue to monitor underwriting agents to
see that they met the required standards and this will take into account the
extent to which they voluntarily purchased such insurance.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
