<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Thai PM calls in former colleagues for cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Anand Panyarachun, Thailand's interim prime minister, yesterday unveiled
a new cabinet, whose main aims will be to restore confidence in the economy
after last month's killings of pro-democracy demonstrators and to prepare
for new elections within four months.
Most of the 26 cabinet members served in Mr Anand's previous government
between the military coup d'etat in February 1991 and the elections in March
this year, although the prime minister was unable to persuade Mr Suthee
Singhasaneh, his choice for the finance portfolio, to take the job.
'Mr Suthee has been in the job for different governments over the past 10
years and he is over 60,' Mr Anand said. The new finance minister is Mr
Panas Simasathien, 59, a US-educated career civil servant who was permanent
secretary in the same ministry.
For the sensitive post of interior minister - the official charged with
organising the new election in a country noted for its corrupt electoral
practices - Mr Anand chose police General Pow Sarasin. He is a member of one
of Thailand's most influential families and at one time was in charge of the
fight against drugs. His brother Arsa Sarasin returns as foreign minister.
Mr Anand was named prime minister by King Bhumipol in a surprise edict last
week to replace the unpopular Gen Suchinda Kraprayoon, who was forced to
resign after the violence last month.
The new premier chose Gen Banchob Bunnag, an uncontroversial retired army
chief of staff, as his defence minister. 'He had a good record in the army,
with no doubtful past, politically or militarily,' said Mr Anand. 'No
involvement in any violent crackdowns, either the recent or earlier ones.'
Foreign investors and the local business community praised the liberalising
economic reforms carried out by the previous Anand administration, and they
are likely to welcome the familiar faces in his cabinet after the turmoil of
the last two months. The ministers of commerce, industry, transport and
communications and agriculture are the same as before.
Thais will now have to wait anxiously to see whether the humiliated military
leaders continue to keep a low profile, and whether the elections will
produce a government which is both acceptable to the demonstrators who
defeated Gen Suchinda and economically competent.
