<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Israel to rent out surplus apartments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Israeli government yesterday decided to rent out thousands of the
surplus apartments it holds as a result of over-estimating immigrant demand
to purchase, writes Hugh Carnegy in Jerusalem. In doing so it has ignored
arguments from the Bank of Israel that the move runs contrary to a pressing
need to reduce the state's role in the economy.
The cabinet voted to make more than 4,600 of some 12,000 empty units
available for rent to the poor and the elderly.
Under the pressure of mass immigration from the former Soviet Union, the
government ordered thousands of apartments to be built in outlying areas,
with a guaranteed buy-back clause. But immigrants' unwillingess to take on
even subsidised mortgages in areas without jobs, and a decline in the rate
of immigration, has left the Housing Ministry facing a loss estimated at up
to Dollars 1bn (Pounds 543m).
</TEXT>
