<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Former Carrian chief to reappear in court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Hong Kong government will tomorrow make its second attempt to gain a
conviction against Mr George Tan, former chairman of the failed Carrian
property and shipping group.
Mr Tan will be brought before the colony's district court to answer eight
charges of bribery. The case will be heard by a judge alone.
Mr Tan is alleged to have paid HKDollars 4.8m (Pounds 338,000) in bribes to
executives of WestLB Asia Ltd and HKDollars 888,000 in bribes and shares to
one executive of Barclays Asia Ltd during 1981 and 1982.
The executive of Barclays, Mr Stuart Turner, pleaded guilty in 1988 to
accepting the bribe and 668,000 shares from Mr Tan. The two WestLB Asia
executives have also pleaded guilty.
The government's attempts to gain a conviction against Mr Tan were
frustrated in 1987 when a judge dismissed charges against him of conspiring
to defraud shareholders. Charges against his auditors, Price Waterhouse, for
false accounting were also dismissed.
The judge, who resigned six months after his controversial ruling, ended
Hong Kong's longest trial after 281 days and a cost to the colony's
exchequer of more than HKDollars 27m.
The colonial government has another case pending against Mr Tan. This is
dependent, however, on the extradition from Britain of Mr Lorrain Osman,
former chairman of Bumiputra Malaysia Finance, a Hong Kong-based subsidiary
of the state-owned Bank Bumiputra, who has been fighting extradition for the
past 6 1/2 years.
Mr Osman, who is the longest serving prisoner on remand in Britain, last
Thursday lost his seventh attempt to have his extradition quashed.
If returned to Hong Kong, Mr Osman will face 42 fraud and corruption charges
connected with HKDollars 6bn on loans made by his company to Carrian.
Carrian was put into liquidation in October 1983 with debts estimated at
more than HKDollars 10bn. The biggest lender to the company was Bumiputra
Malaysia Finance.
Hongkong and Shanghai Bank also lost an undisclosed sum and its subsidiary,
Wardley, was placed under new management.
</TEXT>
