<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / States return to their seats at BIS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank for International Settlements is making a subtle change to the
proceedings of its annual meeting in Basle today. The national flags of
Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia will be flying outside the bank's headquarters
in Basle, alongside those of the BIS's other 29 shareholder central banks.
The Baltic states are returning to take up their seats in the 'central
bankers' bank' for the first time since their annexation by the Soviet Union
in 1940.
Membership of the central bankers' 'club' represents a landmark in the three
states' drive to regain sovereignty. The national banks of Latvia, Lithuania
and Estonia joined the BIS when it was set up in 1930 to help organise
payment of Germany's First World War reparations. They routinely deposited
part of their gold reserves with the BIS, which held the bullion in New
York.
The BIS never recognised the Soviet takeovers, either de facto or de jure.
In contrast to Sweden and Britain, which in 1940 and 1968 respectively
transferred or sold Baltic gold as part of agreements with the Soviet Union,
the BIS maintained the Baltic states' bullion deposits intact during the
whole period after 1940 despite repeated Soviet claims that the gold
belonged to Moscow.
The Baltic assets held with the BIS, along with the three states' other
reconstituted pre-war gold holdings, now make up the lion's share of their
monetary reserves. Britain and Sweden this year both agreed to pay back to
the Baltic states gold deposited in1940.
Britain repaid the gold in March, while Sweden will probably make its own
restitution soon.
The overall importance of the Baltic states' return to the BIS fold is
considerably greater than their actual stakes in the institution. Latvia,
Lithuania and Estonia own between them a mere 2,200 shares in the BIS -
giving them stakes of 0.2, 0.2 and 0.04 per cent respectively.
The BIS was not the only bank which succeeded in hanging on to Baltic gold
in the post-war era. The Bank of France held small amounts of Baltic gold -
1 tonne for Latvia, and 2.3 tonnes for Lithuania. But the French managed to
keep the Baltic gold from both Germany and the Soviet Union during the war
because stocks were sent to Africa for safekeeping. In contrast to the Bank
of England and the Swedish Riksbank, the Bank of France could point out that
it had been a little more successful in conserving customers' deposits
during a stormy half- century.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
