<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / The European Market: German construction companies prepare
for rebuilding of the east - Best growth prospects are beyond W Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACQUISITIONS in western Europe no longer feature on Bilfinger + Berger's
list of priorities, Mr Christian Roth, chairman, said this month. That side
of the business - and the continent - is adequately covered already. B+B,
Germany's third largest construction company, recently tied up a
collaboration package with France's Fougerolle, completing a round of
strategic deals which have covered most of the gaps in the Community market.
Philipp Holzmann, market leader with DM11bn (Pounds 3.7bn) sales, is in a
similar position, It has, for example, a 30 per cent stake in Britain's
Tilbury Douglas and control of Nord-France.
For the present, most attention is focused on long-term prospects in the
east rather than on the slender short-term possibilities of the looming EC
single market. As Mr Hermann Becker, Holzmann's chairman and leader of the
HDB industry association, pointed out last month, the Community construction
market is in a rut. Growth can be expected this year only in Germany and,
thanks to government-funded infrastructural work, Portugal.
While total EC investment in building this year is expected to stick at
about DM1,300bn, commercial construction will be down more than 5 per cent
and member states' budget restrictions have in effect stopped growth in
public works. New EC housing output is forecast to fall 0.5 per cent, and
the only consolation lies in an expected 2.4 per cent rise in the market for
apartment and house refurbishment.
While German builders talk of 'stagnation' this year, they are careful to
point out that the plateau on which they find themselves stands far above
the business landscape in neighbouring community countries. They have shared
handsomely in the boom which has carried German industry upwards since the
late 1980s. Latest figures for B+B, for example, showed a further 20 per
cent increase in sales and a 38 per cent rise in pre-tax profits for 1991.
Holzmann's turnover rose 18 per cent. Holzmann's profits performance, which
is not yet available, is unlikely to be quite so strong because the group
depends on markets abroad for 47 per cent of its business, compared with
B+B's 36 per cent.
Now, while other German industries are mourning the demise of the
post-unification boom - demand for cars and other consumer goods is tailing
off in the former GDR - builders are starting to enjoy properly the benefits
of rebuilding eastern Germany from the drains upwards. New estimates say
there is DM2,000bn-worth of work to be done before eastern housing,
factories, roads, railways and environmental services match those in the
west. Political necessity, according to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, demands that
it is done quickly to prevent westwards migration, or even social unrest.
Despite the presence of foreign companies such as RMC and Tarmac, German
builders have the market pretty much to themselves.
As public spending is squeezed in the west of the country and all available
funds are transferred to the five new states, so the construction industry
refocuses its attention - Philipp Holzmann alone has bought 40 east German
companies in the past two years - and looks beyond to the underdeveloped
infrastructures in Poland, Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
Politicians talk of future EC membership for them, but German builders,
working closely with industry and governments in Warsaw and Prague, have
already redrawn the maps. They show pencilled-in lines criss-crossing
Czechoslovakia and Poland, delineating projects, including all new road and
rail connections sweeping from Frankfurt an der Oder to Warsaw and beyond.
New stretches of rail will connect Stuttgart directly with the Polish
capital, passing through Prague and Wroclaw.
Germany's expectations are as high as the planned links are long. Starting
with the advantages of geographical position and cultural and linguistic
links, the building industry has moved speedily to implant itself in new
markets where the domestic competition is still inexperienced, suffering
from lack of up-to-date know-how and relatively thin on the ground.
Of the 11 joint ventures in building materials and construction established
in Czechoslovakia last year, seven were initiated by west German concerns.
Foreign investors, again led by Germany, spent Koruna26bn (Pounds 500m) in
the first wave of privatisations in the sector. All they need now is the
forecast upswing in the market.
The signs of recovery - estimated growth of 3 or 4 per cent this year
following a 30 per cent nosedive in 1991 - are already there. Meanwhile,
thousands of Czechoslovakia's skilled building workers are being kept
occupied and trained in the German way among the 55,000 east Europeans
currently employed on the federal republic's unique pilot project:
rebuilding the former GDR.
 ----------------------------------------------------------
        EC: REAL CHANGE IN CONSTRUCTION INVESTMENT:
                    YEAR ON YEAR (%)
 ----------------------------------------------------------
                                1990     1991     1992
Germany                         +4.1     +1.8     +3.5
W Germany                       +5.3     +4.1     +1.5
E Germany                       -3.9    -14.0      +17
France                          +2.5     +0.9     -0.2
UK                              +0.8    -10.5     -3.6
Italy                           +2.4     +0.1     -0.4
Spain                           +9.0     +4.0     -1.0
Netherlands                     +1.4     -0.4     -5.7
Belgium                         +7.0     +2.0     -0.6
Denmark                         -3.6     -7.7     -2.0
Portugal                        +5.0     +4.5     +4.0
