<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Insurer to pay rebates to California drivers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROGRESSIVE Insurance Company, the Ohio-based insurer which specialises in
non-standard private passenger car coverage, has agreed to pay Dollars 51.2m
(Pounds 28.1m) in rebates to Californian motor vehicle insurance
policyholders.
The agreement represents further progress for Mr John Garamendi, the
Californian Insurance Commissioner, as he struggles to implement Proposition
103, the state's voter initiative which was passed in 1988.
Prop 103 called for rate rollbacks based on the profitability of car
insurers operating in the states. However, the insurance companies quickly
mounted formidable legal opposition to its provisions, and implementation of
Prop 103 led to a tangled courtroom battle. Progressive is only the third
big insurer to agree to pay out Prop 103 rebates. The others are Auto Club
of Southern California and Mercury Insurance.
Progressive's pay-out will be shared among 260,000 policyholders, providing
them with an average cheque of Dollars 200 apiece. The California Insurance
Department also said that the insurer had agreed to make future rate
reductions for certain private passenger lines and coverages, and to freeze
any rate increases for 12 months.
Progressive's shares were suspended in New York on Friday at Dollars 52 1/4.
</TEXT>
