<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Clinton criticises black 'racism'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton has sharply attacked a black popular singer for
inciting racial prejudice in the US, thus incurring the displeasure of the
country's most prominent black leader, the Rev Jesse Jackson.
The presumptive Democratic presidential candidate took what appears to be a
calculated political gamble in a Washington speech at a meeting of the
Rainbow Coalition, Mr Jackson's own political organisation.
He said Sister Souljah, the black rap singer who had addressed the meeting
the previous night, was on record as saying after the Los Angeles riots that
blacks could be justified in killing whites and that whites had 'a low-down
dirty nature'.
'If you took the words 'white' and 'black' and reversed them, you might
think David Duke was giving that speech,' he said in a reference to the
fringe right-wing politician who performed dismally in a bid for the
Republican nomination this year.
'We have an obligation, all of us, to call attention to prejudice wherever
we see it,' he said. He admired the Rainbow Coalition's determination 'to
come together across racial lines' but felt Sister Souljah's comments ran
counter to that spirit, as had his own admitted mistake of playing golf at a
segregated country club.
Mr Jackson accused Mr Clinton of 'bad judgment' and said the singer deserved
an apology.
The campaigns of both Mr Clinton and President George Bush have been
debating how best to respond to the new political challenges posed by Mr
Ross Perot, the prospective independent candidate.
An option for both is to appeal more openly to their respective liberal and
conservative constituencies, on the grounds that in a close three-way race,
secure natural political bases will be more important than ever.
This explains why Vice-President Dan Quayle has been dispatched to
conservative audiences to attack the liberal values and cultural elitism of
the media. He is also being deployed as the main Republican critic of Mr
Perot.
Mr Clinton, however, is known to believe that excessive reliance on
traditional Democratic constituencies - especially minorities and organised
labour - would be a recipe for failure. His campaign throughout has been
predicated on the need to win back middle-class Americans, mostly white, who
voted Republican in the last three elections, while not sacrificing the
progressive base.
At his press conference last Friday he denied there was tactical division
among his staff on the issue.
Yet his cause would undoubtedly be weakened if the black vote were lost.
Neither Mr Bush nor Mr Perot is popular among blacks, but the critical
question is whether they vote in sufficient numbers to help Mr Clinton.
For that to happen it is axiomatic that he needs the support of leaders like
Mr Jackson.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
