<DOCNO>FT922-2910</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5AAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Survey of Greece (6): Newcomers are making their presence
felt - Banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER may be happening elsewhere in the economy, Greek banking is
thriving. Six new private banks have opened in the past two years, one
state-controlled bank was privatised and three new foreign players joined
the market. This adds up to a 30 per cent increase in Greek banking
institutions.
While it is true that the new banks are small operations, often with no more
than the minimum capitalisation of Dr4bn (Dollars 21m) and only two or three
branches, they are making their presence felt.
It is not only foreign banks and larger private banks that are cutting costs
and thinking hard about new products for a more competitive environment. The
big state-controlled banks, which between them control some 75 per cent of
assets and 80 per cent of loans, are at last starting to modernise.
Life is easier for borrowers as a result, despite interest rates kept high
by inflation. A year ago, rates for working capital hovered around 29 per
cent, rising to more than 33 per cent when taxes and commissions were added.
Now the basic rate is about 23 per cent, although this may depend on a
corporate customer's bargaining power.
'It's a much healthier situation,' says one banker. 'But the mentality of
corporate customers is changing, from relationship banking to shopping
around for a particular deal.'
One advantage enjoyed by the new banks is having to place only 20 per cent
of their reserves in government paper, according to central bank
requirements. The reserve ruling is being phased out altogether over the
next year, but that is not much consolation for older banks which have 40
per cent of their reserves - the regulation amount until last year - tied up
in Treasury bills.
In 1991, the government arranged for Dr1,600bn of these reserves to be
converted into medium-term bonds with a three- to seven-year maturity. The
idea was that they should form the basis of a secondary market in government
securities.
But given the present squeeze in Greek financial markets, with the
government financing the public sector wage and pension bills with monthly
issues of T-bills at attractive rates, this plan proved too optimistic.
Instead, the banks have turned to repos - fixed term selling and repurchase
orders of government debt - in a big way.
Government securities are still tax-free, which accounts for a flight of
savings from the banks last year with the introduction of a 10 per cent tax
on interest earnings on deposit accounts. Bank deposits grew overall by only
5.4 per cent in 1991 to Dr8,856bn. In the first two months of this year,
they showed a decline of Dr105bn.
The crowding-out effect, together with shrinking margins on traditional
lending business, are making all Greek banks look more closely at fee-based
activities. Spreads have fallen sharply as lending rates came down but the
basic savings rate, set by the central bank, remained at 18 per cent.
The new banks are setting up mutual funds and developing private banking as
they try to find the right operating niche. Their specialities range from
shipping lending to mortgage loans and consumer credit. Established banks,
too, have launched mutual funds and moved into leasing and underwriting.
In a country with only 2,400 bank branches to serve a population of 1m,
there is plenty of room for banks to grow. Yet however successful they
become, the private banks will find it increasingly hard to make headway if
the big state banks focus on competing effectively.
'If the state banks can throw off their chains, they have the muscle to push
the rest of us aside,' says a foreign banker.
The impetus for reform at state-controlled banks is coming from new
management appointed by the government last year, consisting of younger
Greek bankers who were working abroad or for foreign banks in Athens. Under
their guidance, the state banks have substantially increased their capital
base over the past 18 months and raised provisions for doubtful loans.
Following the example of some foreign banks, they have strengthened their
dealing rooms to international standards.
As long-overdue investment in new computers is made, automated telling
machines are appearing around Athens branches and the leading tourist
resorts. But no state bank has yet dared to suggest that cheque books and
credit cards should replace the pass-book system, still the basis of
personal banking in Greece.
But the effects of change are beginning to show. Commercial Bank, the second
biggest state bank, reported an 85 per cent increase in profits to Dr35bn.
Its subsidiary, Ionian Bank, also did well with a 42 per cent rise to
Dr15.65bn.
Mr Takis Arapoglou, chairman of Ionian, says: 'We stopped the state bank
accounting practice of accruing unpaid interest on non-performing loans. But
we still have some way to go in clearing up our portfolio.'
If the state banks are to have a chance of becoming efficient, two things
must happen. First, regulations that make it virtually impossible for staff
to be dismissed have to be revised, enabling operating costs to be cut. Like
other public institutions, state banks are a target for making patronage
appointments.
Then the curious legal status of the state banks must be changed so that
they can no longer be used as instruments of government policy. At present,
the finance minister has a proxy vote on behalf of their main shareholders -
the state-controlled insurance companies and welfare funds, the
universities, even the Orthodox Church.
So far the government has proved reluctant to give up this privilege and set
the state banks free.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-2911</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5AAEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Survey of Greece (5): Quickening pace of sales -
Privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE quickening pace of sales this year under Greece's privatisation
programme has come as a relief to the government, but as one official puts
it: 'Once you clear away the undergrowth of small disposals, the real
dimensions of our task looms much larger.'
Privatisation was launched two years ago with the initial aim of selling 27
debt-burdened companies nationalised under Socialist rule. But as the
state-controlled banks - with assets that include shipyards, mines and
quarries, hotels and insurance companies, joined in - the list of companies
to be privatised grew to more than 200.
The government also wants to sell minority stakes of up to 49 per cent in
state-owned utilities and transport companies. Most post losses every year,
the result of weak management and rising costs: administered prices were
kept low while payrolls swelled with political appointees.
But the most ambitious aspect of Greek privatisation is only now taking
shape. Mr Andreas Andrianopoulos, the industry minister and a firm believer
in unbundling the state, intends to dispose of about 300 public entities
attached to different ministries in the next two years.
These range from companies set up to manage industrial projects that never
materialised to moribund trading organisations and farm co-operatives. They
have managed to survive because, like the utilities, they were a convenient
receptacle for patronage appointments.
Mr Andrianopoulos has steered a new privatisation law through parliament
which removes many hurdles to swift liquidation of non-viable companies. The
law also provides a clear legal framework for sales and debt write-offs,
which banks and other creditors were reluctant to attempt for fear of future
lawsuits.
'It's really more a process of denationalisation than privatisation, because
the state is an obstacle to growth,' he said recently.
Opposition to Mr Andrianopoulos's scheme comes as much from cabinet
colleagues as from boards of directors afraid of losing their jobs or
customers anxious to maintain a cosy relationship with a state-controlled
producer. Some ministers at first declined to provide lists of companies
under their jurisdiction; others sent in a few names scrawled on a sheet of
paper.
For all the government's avowed commitment to privatising, it is clear that
the old etatist mentality still persists. For example, Depa, a utility set
up to supervise construction of a pipeline and liquified natural gas
terminal for importing Russian and Algerian natural gas to Greece, is to
remain state-owned.
In theory, the next stage of the Dr250bn (Dollars 1.2bn) project, creating
networks for distributing the gas in leading Greek cities, should be open to
bids from private companies under the government's policy of making the
energy sector more competitive. In practice, the absence of a regulatory
framework for power generation rules out broader participation, for the time
being.
Elsewhere, privatisation is gaining momentum after a slow start. The 1991
budget forecast revenues of more than Dr150bn from sales of nationalised
companies, but only Dr10bn was raised. 'Transparency was important, and it
took time to get international procedures working in the bureaucratic Greek
environment,' says one adviser.
However, 22 of the 27 companies offered by the Industrial Reconstruction
Organisation (IRO), the socialists' nationalisation umbrella, have now been
sold. Buyers have mostly been local competitors rather than foreign
investors.
The exception was Heracles General Cement, Europe's biggest cement exporter,
sold for Dr124bn to a joint venture between Calcestruzzi, the construction
arm of Italy's Ferruzzi group, and National Bank of Greece. The
participation of National Bank, the country's largest state-owned bank, was
seen as essential in order to overcome legal problems caused by the
capitalisation of Dr27bn in debt owed by Heracles. The capitalisation was in
violation of European Community company law because shareholders were not
consulted.
If the capitalisation is eventually declared invalid, National Bank will
revert to being the largest shareholder in Heracles. Calcestruzzi, with a
52.5 per cent stake in the joint venture, will be responsible for running
the company.
The state-owned banks between them have sold another 30 companies, again to
local rather than foreign buyers. The biggest disposal was that of Eleusis
Shipyards, sold by Commercial Bank for Dollars 60m to the Peraticos group, a
London-based Greek shipping business.
Another three loss-making shipyards, also controlled by state banks, must be
sold or shut down over the next few months in order to meet an EC deadline
for ending subsidies to the shipbuilding industry. The yards were taken over
by the state after an older generation of Greek shipowners pulled out of
onshore investment in Greece during the shipping crisis of the early 1980s.
Despite a steady flow of repair work and some construction of small vessels
for the Greek navy, the yards were kept going through cash infusions from
the state banks, with little attention paid to improving productivity. The
EC has agreed to the writing off of large amounts of debt; even so, the
government is finding it difficult to attract offers. The most attractive
target for buyers is the Hellenic Telecommunications Organisation (OTE), the
state telecoms monopoly, which is to be partially privatised. A 49 per cent
stake will be offered in two stages. With earnings in 1991 of Dr55bn, OTE is
one of Greece's most profitable companies, despite operating little more
than an old-fashioned telephone network with only a few digital exchanges
and a chronic shortage of lines.
A new regulatory framework, drawn up with assistance from the EC and
international legal experts, will be in place later this year. The
government intends to offer a 20-30 per cent stake in OTE to an
international operator, who would also take over management, with the
remaining percentage being sold through a public offering in Greece and
abroad.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-2912</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5AADFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Survey of Greece (2): Home to roost, with a vengeance - The
Economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER years of fiscal profligacy, mismanagement of the large
state-controlled economic sectors and market distortions caused by
over-regulation and protection, Greece has finally had to face up to the
dire economic problems which it has so long feigned to ignore.
It is ironic that it is the very European Community which Greece joined in
1981 - and which it has always regarded as a generous provider of funds
rather than as a law-maker whose rules must be obeyed - that should now be
one of the main instruments forcing Greece to put its economic house in
order. The goose that laid the golden eggs has come home to roost with a
vengeance.
The results of the austerity measures introduced by the conservative New
Democracy government led by Mr Constantine Mitsotakis, since it came to
power in April 1990, have been described as 'inadequate' and 'seriously out
of line with targets' by the European Commission in a remarkably damning
report issued last March.
It is widely recognised that the prime minister faced an extremely difficult
task. After nearly a decade of socialist government under Mr Andreas
Papandreou, he inherited a disastrous economic situation marked by a soaring
public deficit, a public debt-GDP ratio much higher than that of any of the
Latin American states at the height of their worst crises and a rate of
inflation at least 2.5 times the average in the EC.
A paper-thin majority of only two parliamentary seats has not made the prime
minister's task any easier. However, Mr Mitsotakis's critics - some of whom
can be found inside his own party - complain that too much valuable time was
lost by the New Democracy government before it started implementing a
three-year stabilisation programme at the beginning of last year. The
publicity-shy Mr Stefanos Manos, the new economics minister, is reputed to
share this view and wants to press ahead with more radical stabilisation
measures.
However, Mr Mitsotakis is fast running out of time. The next general
election is due in 1994 and political expediency dictates that no really
unpopular measures are taken by the government in the last year of its term.
That means, failing a political death-wish entirely uncharacteristic of
Greek politicians, that the administration of any really effective economic
medicine can be virtually ruled out from 1993 onwards.
Even the European Commission, frustrated as it undoubtedly is after years of
preaching in the wilderness, recognises that some useful steps have been
taken by the government to prepare the Greek economy for the EC's Single
Market. Significant progress has been made, particularly in liberalising
international capital movements and the domestic financial system.
Long-term capital movements have been liberalised and controls have been
lifted on current international transactions. Credit controls have been
abolished, staged cuts in the special reserve requirements of banks are
being made, and the state's right to borrow directly from the central bank
through the obligatory purchase by banks of Treasury Bills is being phased
out.
Price controls on a broad range of goods and services have been lifted, wage
indexation has been abolished and replaced by a strict incomes policy for
the public sector, a freeze in the hiring of public sector employees has
been in effect since last year and the oil market is in the process of being
deregulated.
The privatisation programme is also, at last, being implemented at a more
reasonable pace. In 1991, some 14 of the so-called 'problematic enterprises'
had been sold and 11 liquidated, followed in March this year by the sale of
70 per cent of the Heracles cement company
A long-awaited tax reform package - aimed at boosting inadequate national
revenues, at least in the longer run, broadening the tax base and curbing
Greeks' favourite pastime of tax evasion by the imposition of stricter
penalties and the confiscation of professional licences - was finally tabled
in parliament in May, although its eventual shape remains problematical.
On the external front, too, the news has been much better. The current
account deficit fell by as much as 60 per cent last year to Dollars 1.46bn,
scarcely more than 2 per cent of GDP. This was thanks mainly to large net
inflows of invisibles, particularly from the EC, which account for as much
as 25 per cent of Greece's invisible earnings. A marked decline in imports,
as the result of the domestic recession, also contributed substantially to
the much-improved balance of payments performance.
All these positive developments, however, cannot compensate for the
economy's fundamental failings. Until the large public deficit is brought
under control and the huge debt overhang begins to be reduced, a sustainable
economic recovery is not achievable.
The net public sector borrowing requirement (PSBR) of 14.1 per cent of GDP
in 1991, although lower than the previous year and a great improvement on
the 20 per cent figure when the government took office, was still 3.7
percentage points higher than the objective set by the government. The
target is to reduce the deficit to 9.1 per cent of GDP in 1992, but given
what are considered by independent experts as the over-optimistic budget
forecasts for tax and privatisation revenues, the out-turn is likely to be
at least 2 points higher.
The high fiscal deficit has undoubtedly contributed to the persistence of
inflation at an unacceptably high level by EC standards of about 18 per cent
since the summer of last year. Prospects that the annual rate for 1992 as a
whole will fall any lower than about 16 per cent, in spite of the
maintenance of tight monetary conditions, restrictive incomes policies and
weak demand, are considered to be dim.
However, as the EC Commission report said: 'the magnitude of the problem is
not to be seen simply in the scale of the deficits, but in the underlying
financial fragility.'
Public sector debt is now equivalent to as much as 135 to 140 per cent of
GDP. Significant debt-servicing problems arose in 1991, leading the
government to reschedule its own debt in addition to already existing
capitalisation of debt interest. The resulting postponement of debt
servicing has stored financial problems for Greek governments in future
years.
The remedies are clear. If Greece is to fulfil the tough terms for the
second tranche of the Ecu2.2bn (Pounds 1.54bn) loan granted to it
conditionally by the EC last year, the government will have to make another
huge adjustment effort. That will require substantial public spending cuts
and further structural reforms, involving sharp reductions in both the wage
bill and staffing levels of state-owned enterprises and the early
implementation of proposals for reforming the social security system.
The problem is not so much what to do as how to make it palatable to a
political class and society chronically affected by the disease of
'short-termism.' The government's almost impossible task is to persuade the
Greek people that any further delay in the implementation of radical
solutions will inevitably lead to the permanent marginalisation of Greece in
the European Community.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
