<DOCNO>FT922-2915</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFOA5AAAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920615
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUN 92 / Survey of Greece (1): Urgent need for reforms - Greece's
economic troubles show few signs of abating. A stabilisation programme
launched last year with the aim of closing the gap with the rest of the EC
has fallen far behind schedule. Structural reforms that would curtail
spending have been postponed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR all its years of European Community membership, Greece sometimes bears
more resemblance to its Balkan neighbours than to its European partners.
The current outburst of nationalist feeling against recognising Macedonia,
the former Yugoslav republic adjoining northern Greece, is a case in point.
Senior officials will discuss arcane aspects of regional history with an
eloquence that is lacking when the question of preparations for European
monetary union comes up.
Yet Greece's economic troubles show few signs of abating. The stabilisation
programme launched last year with the aim of closing the gap with the rest
of the EC, has fallen well behind schedule.
This was not entirely unexpected, given that extremely stiff terms were
agreed with the European Commission in return for an Ecu2.2bn (Pounds
1.54bn) special loan in three instalments.
But in addition to missing the targets set for curbing inflation and the
ballooning public sector deficit, the government postponed launching
structural reforms that would effectively curtail spending.
The result is a prolonged period of embarrassment for Mr Constantine
Mitsotakis, the prime minister, and Mr Stefanos Manos, his new economy
minister.
They cannot ask for payment of the second tranche of the loan until some
lost ground has been made up and the Commission approves the Greek plan for
achieving economic convergence with its EC partners by 1997.
Mr Manos, a former businessman who trained at Harvard, is well aware that
despite the uncertainty generated by the Danish decision to reject the
Maastricht treaty, structural reform remains urgent.
The Greek predicament was recently underlined by Portugal's entry to the
exchange rate mechanism (ERM) of the European Monetary System, which leaves
the drachma as the only currency outside the system. Even the most
optimistic of Greek bankers believe that it will be at least another year
before the inflation rate drops enough for Greek entry to be possible.
However, Mr Mitsotakis is an old-fashioned politician who finds it difficult
to resist pressure from special interest groups. In public he stresses the
danger that because of its weak economy, Greece will not be able to function
as an equal partner in the Community.
Yet he appears to condone delay as the price of eventually winning cabinet
acceptance for the measures proposed by Mr Manos and his advisers.
Mr Manos advocates another five years of austerity, with minimal wage
increases and deep spending cuts with the aim of halving the deficit by
1997.
Growth would be stimulated by increased EC assistance - including the new
'cohesion fund' for poorer members - for important projects to improve
transport and telecommunications.
But with a rebellious cabinet and only a one-seat majority in parliament, Mr
Mitsotakis feels obliged to tread cautiously. Several of his potential
successors as leader of the conservative New Democracy party are no longer
members of the government. At present, Mr Mitsotakis is also his own foreign
minister, having sacked the youthful foreign minister, Mr Antonis Samaras,
in a well-publicised dispute over his handling of the Macedonian problem.
Ask a constituency worker in New Democracy why economic reform is so
painfully slow and the answer comes at once: 'Political cost.' It is clear
to almost everyone that the measures demanded by the terms of the EC loan
will deal a fatal blow to the all-pervasive patronage system by which the
ruling party rewards its supporters with public sector jobs. Modernisation
of the civil service is proving one of the most contentious issues. The
government agreed to trim 50,000 jobs by 1993, amounting to 10 per cent of
the civil service payroll. But as the Commission pointed out in a recent
report on the Greek economy, instead of shrinking, the number of civil
servants grew by 4.4 per cent last year.
The government has decided to tackle the other potentially explosive problem
first: overhauling the welfare system in order to reduce pension outlays
which, together with wages, add up to about 40 per cent of budget spending.
Proposals from an experts' committee include gradually raising the
pensionable age to 60 by the end of the decade and extending years of
service. Women, for example, will no longer qualify for a pension in their
mid-30s after only 15 years in a job.
A fierce reaction to the changes is expected, led by the Panhellenic
Socialist Movement (Pasok), whose generous welfare policies in the 1980s,
combined with a disregard for revenue-raising, are held responsible for the
present impasse.
Mr Andreas Papandreou, the Pasok leader, is in more vigorous form after his
acquittal by a special court of corruption while in office.
His health appears to have improved, while the prospect of mounting a
campaign against the government's restrictive social policies cannot fail to
appeal to his populist instincts.
Support for the government has weakened with the imposition this year of a
wage freeze in the public sector. Several thousand jobs have been lost
through sales and closures of debt-ridden nationalised companies under the
government's wide-ranging privatisation programme.
Unemployment is rising, especially among the young and unskilled whose
chances of finding a job are reduced by the presence of more than 150,000
Albanian, Bulgarian and Polish immigrants working illegally in Greece.
However, the mood is brighter in the private sector.
Businessmen say they are well placed to take advantage of the reforms that
have been introduced. Almost all price controls have been lifted in the past
year. A new tax law making its way through parliament provides for deep cuts
in corporation tax and sharply reduced income tax for both high and low
earners.
Despite gloomy predictions, no massive flight of capital followed the
lifting of curbs on medium-term capital movement. In fact, business
confidence improved, with capital inflows remaining at fairly high levels.
There is now talk of liberalising remaining exchange controls by 1993,
rather than seeking a two-year postponement already sanctioned by the
Community. In the view of many bankers, this could help bring home a
substantial proportion of the estimated Dollars 10bn held by Greeks in
overseas bank accounts.
While the Foreign Ministry flaunts its disagreements with Balkan neighbours,
Greek businessmen are quietly developing contacts. Greece is officially
annoyed with Bulgaria for recognising Macedonian independence and for
drawing closer to its traditional enemy, Turkey.
But the flourishing Greek food-processing industry is starting to invest
there, and a growing list of joint ventures includes manufacturing units on
both sides of the border.
Even in Albania, where relations are dogged by mutual suspicion and official
recriminations over treatment of the North Epirots, the ethnic Greek
minority in the south of the country, tentative steps are being taken.
Greeks are involved in a number of farming projects and small textile
plants.
Still, Greece cannot make a lasting contribution to the development of
market economies in the Balkans unless the muddle over recognising Macedonia
is cleared up and its own economy is on the road to convergence.
If Mr Mitsotakis continues his delays, both this and the other opportunities
offered by closer European co-operation will simply disappear.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
