<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 92 / International Company News: PacTel considers sale of 8 UK
cable franchises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PACIFIC Telesis, one of the regional telecommunications companies which
resulted from the break-up of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, said yesterday
it was considering selling its eight cable franchises in the UK.
PacTel claimed to be entertaining the move so that it could 'focus solely on
its wireless telecommunications business'. 'We still find the UK cable TV
market attractive,' commented Mr Lee Cox, PacTel's chief executive, 'but we
want to concentrate our efforts on winning more valuable cellular and paging
licences abroad.'
The company, based in Walnut Creek, California, is currently pursuing
cellular licences in a range of countries - from Japan and Hong Kong to
Greece and Spain in continental Europe. Its parent, Pacific Telesis Group is
also studying proposals which could involve spinning off the Pacific Bell
and Nevada Bell phone operations, but yesterday's announcement was said to
be independent of this.
PacTel suggested that it was flexible about how it restructured the UK cable
franchises - with options under consideration ranging from an outright sale,
to some form of joint venture deal. Officials said that preliminary talks
with potential purchasers or partners had already taken place.
PacTel built up its UK cable TV franchises in the late 1980s. Of the eight
to be 'restructured', four are operational - in the Peterborough, Bolton,
Derby and Norwich areas - with around 10,000 subscribers. The other licences
are in Manchester, Doncaster and several smaller cities. In total, the
company is licensed to serve about 1m homes.
It recently sold its east London cable properties to BCE Telecom
International, for an undisclosed amount.
</TEXT>
