<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Investors could be spoiled for choice -
Richard Gourlay looks at the spate of impending stock exchange flotations
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS LOOKING for some excitement will be spoiled for choice from the
raft of new companies about to be floated on the stock exchange.
Those with memories that stretch back to the pre-big bang spate of
flotations may remember that they frequently either went spectacularly well
or were comprehensive flops.
This time around, the flotations are likely to be different. In the first
place, the size is generally significantly larger than those in the mid
1980s.
Many of them, like GPA, Wellcome and 3i are long established companies
rather than new entities that have grown rapidly and are coming to market
with relatively little following.
In short, the markets and the companies are likely to be better understood
and pricing should be more competitive - that is to say, there will be less
opportunity for huge premiums after flotation.
In that sense, analysts say, many of the flotations will resemble recent
privatisations where the companies generally operated in known markets with
known managements.
From the companies' point of view, many will be floating to reduce
management buy-out gearing and to allow managements to emerge from under the
shadow of personal guarantees secured on their houses to an altogether
rosier world.
But for others there is a very 1990s motivation. As the economy moves into
recovery, they are being forced to finance their growth from internal
resources as the big banks' are far less willing to lend. There is no
central register of flotations so the chart belowmay not be comprehensive.
</TEXT>
