<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 92 / Arts: Soul's little madam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LISA Stansfield is in danger of turning into a proper little madam. When
last seen, a couple of years ago, this fantasy figure who made an ass of
pure reason by coming from nowhere - well, Rochdale actually - to top the US
soul charts, retained a Lancashire lass charm. With her cap worn the wrong
round and a tendency to skip around the stage like a mixed infant allowed
home early, she undermined the critical faculties with the same ease as Our
Gracie.
Now, at Wembley, millions of record sales later, she lies astride a packing
case stroking her body meaningfully and nibbling her hand mike with all the
subtlety of Ruby Wax as she purrs 'Time to make you mine'. Lisa seems
destined to join Olivia Newton-John and Sheena Easton as a nut-brown
Hollywood Queen, dragging herself away from the pool to do Vegas.
Fortunately she still gives a northern stretch to the 'a' as she tells us we
are free to 'dance', but it took two pointed reminders before the Wembley
crowd staggered to its feet to boogie modestly. To the nation's loss, Lisa
Stansfield has been transformed into a soul superstar with a packaged show
of faceless musicians.
At the start the packaging was too constricting. Bass and percussion were
winning over a voice which is still packed with power but bereft of
sensitivity. Gradually things fell into shape, especially on the slower
numbers, but there was plenty of time to think about her outfit - initially
frock coat over black stockings, then hot pants and Rochdale Hornet yellow
and black striped blouse - and her appearance (a forties perm and shiney
make-up) rather than to be transported away on that old soul train.
The old hits - 'All around the world'; 'This is the right time' - were kept
for the end, but by then I was nostalgic for the pert 24-year-old who was
still so in love with music, and her own voice, that she could try out
Billie Holiday's haunting 'Good Morning Heartbreak' in the middle of her
set. This 26-year-old is in danger of falling into that strange irony
whereby soul singers inevitably pervert the emotional intensity that is the
source of soul music into a mechanical, beat dominated, superficiality of
showmanship.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
