<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 92 / International Company News: Indian bank sets aside Dollars
250m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STATE Bank of India, India's largest public investment bank, is to set aside
Dollars 250m to cover possible losses in the fallout from the country's
worst financial scandal, AP-DJ reports from Bombay.
The government-owned State Bank has agreed to honour liabilities arising
from illegal securities transactions with a leading Bombay stockbroker, bank
officials said.
The broker, Harshad Mehta, has been accused of illegally using bank money to
manipulate stocks.
The Reserve Bank of India, the central bank, ordered the State Bank two
weeks ago to account for Dollars 250m that it had received in crossed
cheques from the National Housing Bank.
Both the State Bank and Housing Bank are subsidiaries of the central bank.
According to police reports, the State Bank credited the money in securities
to Mehta.
Losses by at least nine banks, including Standard Chartered Bank Australia.
and ANZ Grindlays, totalled an estimated Dollars 1.1bn. Except for two small
Indian banks which went bankrupt, the banks were expected to shore up enough
funds to protect their investors.
The State Bank said it could bear the loss of Dollars 250m, even though that
was more than six times the bank's 1990 profits.
</TEXT>
