<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OWEN &amp; Robinson, the jewellery and sports shoe retailer, reported an
increase in pre-tax losses from Pounds 638,000 to Pounds 2.9m for the year
to January 31, and again is not paying a final dividend.
It was also announced yesterday that Mr Maurice Dwek, chairman, had resigned
as head of Arlen, the electricals group, and was expected to devote more
time to O&amp;R.
Mr Dwek, who ran Dwek Group, a mini-conglomerate, and set up Seaforth
Investments, an industrial investment group, has brought in new management
at O&amp;R. Mr Alan Gaynor, who ran the Underwoods chemist chain, and Mr Mike
Smith, formerly finance director of Laura Ashley, arrived in April.
Mr Gaynor said yesterday that they had already identified and removed
overheads, saving Pounds 1m in a full year. This had involved 100
redundancies. He said the core Gold Centre business was sound but had
expanded too fast, almost doubling in size last year.
As a result, group sales rose 45 per cent to Pounds 26.3m in 1991-92.
However, gross profits were held back by price cutting in the all-important
Christmas period.
Exceptional costs of Pounds 832,000 and an extraordinary debit of Pounds
1.15m (Pounds 5.48m), the dividends on the preference shares and the cost of
the 0.15p interim dividend, meant a transfer from reserves of Pounds 5m
(Pounds 6.9m). Losses per share were 11.62p (8.08p).
