</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALOMON Brothers, the New York investment bank recovering from last year's
Treasury bond auction scandal, yesterday moved to strengthen its battered US
equity operation with the appointment of Mr Rodney Berens as co-head of the
department.
Mr Berens, 47, formerly in charge of global research at Morgan Stanley, will
share responsibility for the department with its existing head, Mr Bruce
Hackett, and like him will join the executive committee which runs the
securities firm.
Mr Berens left Morgan Stanley last year for private business.
Salomon's equity department suffered a substantial number of resignations
late last year and early this as the group implemented a wide-ranging
shake-up of its management practices in the wake of the scandal.
This led to a widespread belief on Wall Street - strongly denied by Salomon
 -that the firm was scaling back its commitment to equities.
